      <section>
        <h2>About This Project</h2>
        <p>
          This is a simple neural network trained on the MNIST dataset, which contains 70,000 images
          of handwritten digits. The model learns to recognize patterns in the pixel values and can
          classify digits with high accuracy.
        </p>

        <h3>How It Works</h3>
        <p>
          The MNIST classifier uses a feedforward neural network architecture. When you draw on the
          32x32 grid, each pixel's intensity (0 for white, 1 for black) is fed into the network as
          input. The network consists of:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Input layer:</strong> 1024 neurons (32x32 pixels)</li>
          <li><strong>Hidden layers:</strong> Multiple layers with ReLU activation functions</li>
          <li><strong>Output layer:</strong> 10 neurons (one for each digit 0-9) with softmax activation</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The model was trained using PyTorch on the standard MNIST training set, achieving over 95%
          accuracy on the test set. The training process involved optimizing the network's weights
          using backpropagation and the Adam optimizer.
        </p>

        <h3>Key Concepts</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Supervised Learning:</strong> The model learns from labeled examples, where each
            image is paired with its correct digit label.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs):</strong> While this is a simple feedforward
            network, more advanced MNIST classifiers use CNNs to better capture spatial patterns in images.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Gradient Descent:</strong> The optimization algorithm that adjusts the network's
            weights to minimize prediction error.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Model Details</h3>
        <p>
          The model is hosted on HuggingFace and can be accessed via their Inference API. The input
          is a flattened array of 1024 values (32x32 grid), and the output is a probability distribution
          over the 10 possible digits.
        </p>

        <h3>Try It Out</h3>
        <p>
          The drawing interface above lets you experiment with the model. Try drawing different styles
          of digits and see how the model responds. You might notice:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>The model works best with centered, clearly drawn digits</li>
          <li>Certain digits (like 1 and 7) might be confused if drawn ambiguously</li>
          <li>The model's confidence varies based on how "typical" your drawing looks</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Technologies Used</h3>
